Starting with the given expression:

\begin{align*}
x\left(x(1+x)+2x\right)-3(x^2-x+2)
\end{align*}

We can start by simplifying the expressions within the parentheses:

\begin{align*}
x(x+x^2+2x)-3(x^2-x+2)
\end{align*}

Then, we can simplify the terms inside each group, by combining like terms:

\begin{align*}
x(2x+x^2)-3(x^2-x+2)
\end{align*}

Next, we can distribute the $x$ and $-3$:

\begin{align*}
2x^2+x^3-3x^2+3x-6
\end{align*}

Rearranging the terms in decreasing order of exponents:

\begin{align*}
x^3-3x^2+2x^2+3x-6
\end{align*}

Combining like terms:

\begin{align*}
x^3-x^2+3x-6
\end{align*}

Therefore, the expanded and simplified form of the expression is $x^3-x^2+3x-6$.
